<TEXT>
amnesty international on monday charged 
brazilian police routinely torture and kill criminal suspects with 
the complacency of government authorities 
according to the londonbased human rights organization a 
growing number of victims of torture and illtreatment are 
children aged 18 and under 
the charges were in a 17page report titled torture and 
extrajudicial execution in urban brazil that was released during 
a news conference at the sao paulo branch of the brazilian bar 
association 
political prisoners were routinely tortured during the military 
regimes that ruled this country from 196485 abuses diminished but 
did not end with the return of civilian rule according to amnesty 
torture continues to be endemic in brazil and can happen at 
any time and anywhere in police stations and vehicles in prisons 
and in secret the report said 
while this country of 150 million residents has no more 
political prisoners criminal suspects are still subject to torture 
and illtreatment amnesty said 
there is evidence that the police have responded to increasing 
social violence by taking the law into their own hands torturing 
and killing ordinary criminal suspects and prisoners torture is an 
everyday occurrence in brazil and extrajudicial execution is 
common the report said 
rights violations are not official policy it said but to 
tolerate these abuses is to condone them the alarming incidence of 
unlawful killing torture and cruel and inhuman treatement of 
citizens in official custody indicates the authorities are not 
taking effective steps to eradicate these practices 
at the news conference bacre waly ndiaye vicechairman of the 
organizations international executive committee said policemen 
knowing their crimes will go unpunished because of the 
prevailing climate of impunity form death squads whose victims are 
those least able to defend themselves the poor and children 
death squads kill at least one child a day ndiaye said 
the report said the lack of public confidence in the ability of 
police to deal with the growing crime rate stimulates the growth of 
death squads and vigilante groups known as justiceiros 
portuguese for justicemakers 
justiceiros active in the industrial suburbs of sao paulo are 
paid by local businessmen to eliminate suspected petty criminals 
the report said 
the respected folha de sao paulo newspaper reported in june that 
justiceiros had killed about 40 people in 45 days 
ndiaye said officials admit torture is one of the main 
techniques used to solve crimes and that confessions obtained 
through torture were often used as evidence 
it is time for the brazilian government to take action against 
the growing number of human rights violations and respect the 
countrys constitution by doing nothing it is not only condoning 
but encouraging these abuses ndiaye said 
brazils 1988 constitution states that no one shall be 
subjected to torture or to inhuman or degrading treatment it 
stipulates that the crime of torture is not subject to bail 
amnesty pardon or statute of limitations 
amnestys report also denounced the systematic torture of 
inmates in many of brazils overcrowded prisons 
in april 1989 nearly 91000 prisoners were jammed into prisons 
built to hold less than 44000 it said 
the report was the result of four years of research and was 
based on a series of factfinding visits and meetings with 
authorities local rights organizations lawyers torture victims 
and their relatives 
</TEXT>
