<TEXT>
the usjapan security pact reaches its 30th 
anniversary this month its like an old pair of shoes 
it pinched a bit when new but now its wellworn and 
comfortable 
the pacts anniversary comes as the soviet bloc disbands and 
western allies in nato seek fundamental changes in their alliance 
us and japanese officials suggest no correspondingly 
fundamental look at their defense alliance although voices in both 
countries have called for change some saying the treaty is no 
longer needed 
that is a shortsighted analysis said koichiro matsuura 
directorgeneral of the north american bureau in the foreign 
ministry we do need it for the foreseeable future there are 
still sources of instability in the far east 
yet some regional problems show signs of easing chinesesoviet 
relations have warmed a beginning of rapprochement between south 
korea and the soviet union could ease tension on the divided korean 
peninsula an end to cambodias 11yearold civil war may be in 
sight 
the united states is reducing its troop strength in the far 
east now 135000 by 14000 or 15000 over three years without 
cutting combat capability 
while the united states will enjoy a drop in defense spending 
it calls on prosperous japan and south korea to assume greater 
responsibility for their own defense 
washington wants tokyo to boost the 3 billion it spends 
annually to support the 50000 us troops based in japan the 
government says it will do all it can but sharp questions are 
being asked in japan 
the liberalleaning asahi shimbuns aera magazine recently ran a 
long article questioning whether japan has had a free ride on 
defense as some assert in the us congress asahi shimbun said 
japan provides scarce land rentfree for us bases and goes beyond 
the treatys requirements in paying billions to support us troops 
the article said japanese military commanders reacted angrily to 
a washington post story quoting maj gen henry stackpole of the 
us marine corps as saying us forces in japan were a cork in 
the bottle to prevent japan from rearming 
such a comment means us troops are not partners in defense but 
merely occupying japan as they did after the war the japanese 
officers were quoted as saying anonymously 
the pentagon quickly said stackpoles remarks were not us 
government policy 
we were very happy to hear that matsuura said 
but both washington and tokyo come close to saying the same 
thing arguing that the treaty does not hold japan down but rather 
permits japan to have security under the us umbrella without a 
military buildup that could make its neighbors nervous 
matsuura acknowledged that other asian countries see that 
because japan has the security treaty with the united states japan 
can remain to be a small or medium power 
the 1960 treaty replaced the unequal 1952 treaty that was 
negotiated while the united states was fighting the korean war the 
1952 treaty granted the united states the right to base troops in 
japan but did not obligate it to defend the country 
the treaty also admonished japan not to develop an offensive 
military capability repeating a major aim of the us occupation 
of defeated japan that the country not be permitted again to 
threaten its neighbors 
the revised treaty did not include that cork in the bottle 
and it obliged the united states to defend japan which has a 
nowar clause in its postwar constitution 
in 1960 the streets of tokyo were convulsed by antitreaty 
demonstrations president dwight d eisenhowers plan to visit 
japan was called off amid fear for his safety those signing 
petitions against the treaty were said to number 13 million 6 
million held protest work stoppages 
their argument was not so much antiamerican but more a fear 
that the treaty could drag japan into war 
the conservative government rammed a bill ratifying the treaty 
through parliament on june 23 that year with the opposition absent 
on a protest walkout 
the united statesjapan security treaty of 1960 does not need to 
be renewed either party may give notice to the other of its 
intention to end the agreement and it would expire one year later 
the treatys anniversary will be marked with receptions in tokyo 
and washington and president bush and prime minister toshiki kaifu 
have scheduled a telephone conversation to praise the durable 
relationship 
yet underneath the selfcongratulations lie challenges to the 
word and spirit of the treaty 
friction over trade problems and technology could weaken the 
web of the alliance leaders in both countries cite this danger as 
a major reason for making sure the economic frictions are resolved 
the diminished soviet threat undercuts the rationale for the 
treaty tokyo and washington say the pact is a geopolitical anchor 
on which japan can negotiate with the soviets over disputed islands 
in the kuril chain off northern japan 
japans socialists who oppose the treaty are enjoying a 
political revival they say that if they took over the government 
they would not abruptly change the treaty but their longterm aim 
is to make japan a neutral unarmed nation 
socialist lawmaker tadatoshi akiba said the treaty will not be 
necessary sometime in the future maybe it will disappear 
without anyone noticing 
relations with the united states have gone far beyond security 
matters he said citing recent trade negotiations that seek to 
change each countrys society to reduce trade frictions 
</TEXT>
