<TEXT>
shifting winds pushed an oil slick from 
the supertanker mega borg northeastward sunday buying officials a 
little more time to prepare for when it reaches shore the coast 
guard said 
its switched from traveling northnorthwest to 
northnortheast overnight said petty officer mark sedwick 
that was good because it bought us some time staying parallel to 
shore now its running east of galveston and towards louisiana 
but that could change 
officials alerted communities north of galveston to louisiana 
that the tar balls may not be far away 
coast guard officials late sunday predicted tar balls from the 
spill would hit land tuesday 
its moving slow it didnt move any significant amount 
today petty officer david oney said 
the 30mile slick which lingered about 11 miles offshore had 
stretched into a light sheen in places and continued to drift 
slowly away from the tanker crippled 57 miles offshore from 
galveston since a june 8 explosion but officials said sunday that 
the leaking had apparently stopped and the threat of a new fire had 
ebbed 
coast guard officials also lowered the spill estimate from 46 
million gallons to 39 million gallons officials said sunday that 
