<TEXT>
here is a brief look at the joint economic plan signed sunday by 
five central american presidents at the conclusion of their 
threeday economic summit in antigua guatemala 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
main points the newly formed central american economic 
community will try to mesh the regions economies with coordinated 
action on foreign trade and debt on rebuilding infrastructures on 
agricultural and industrial policy and attracting investment 
the central american economic action plan calls for creation of 
a new set of rules in the region for eliminating obstacles to 
integrated economic growth it calls for the cutting of 
bureaucratic red tape in the transportation of passengers and 
freight in the region it also calls for making customs and 
migration procedures less complicated 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
participants nicaraguan president violeta barrios de chamorro 
and costa rican president rafael calderon both elected this year 
signed the plan as firsttime participants in a regional summit 
signing for guatemala was president vinicio cerezo for el 
salvador president alfredo cristiani and for honduras president 
rafael callejas panamanian president guillermo endara signed as an 
invited observer 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
timing ongoing negotiations between the central american 
governments are necessary to turn the plan into action the 
presidents say in a sixpage document they say that within one 
month bankers and financiers should set up a forum to handle 
central americas foreign debt 
within three months all countries in the region are to present 
tariff regulations offering reciprocal treatment on trade duties 
and government and private sector councils are to be in place to 
allow a dialogue for development a joint agriculture policy for 
food exports and imports is to be designed within three months 
within six months the presidents expect to have a program in 
place for improved transportation telephone mail electricity and 
customs services a strategy for boosting research science and 
technology would then be devised 
also within six months a program should be devised to help 
small businesses underground enterprises and less affluent sectors 
of society share in regional development 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

