<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to hear an 
appeal by columbia sc officials and a billboard company jointly 
found to have violated federal antitrust law 
the court said it will review a ruling that the city and company 
conspired to exclude a rival advertising firm from putting up new 
billboards 
the rival company omni outdoor advertising inc was awarded 3 
million by a federal jury in 1986 
the award was overturned by a trial judge but reinstated last 
december by the 4th us circuit court of appeals 
the appeals court ordered columbia outdoor advertising inc to 
pay the sum and barred city officials from enforcing an ordinance 
the appeals court said was aimed at giving that company a virtual 
billboard monopoly in the city 
omnis lawsuit said columbia outdoor advertising established its 
dominance in the city through the lifelong friendship of its 
principal owner j willis cantey with mayor kirkman finlay he no 
longer is columbias mayor 
the jury also heard evidence that columbia outdoor advertising 
gave finlay and columbia city council members either free or 
reducedrate space on its billboards for their political ads 
the council in 1982 adopted a moratorium on billboard 
construction that blocked omni from entering the market 
after a state court declared the moratorium unconstitutional it 
was replaced the same year with an ordinance requiring billboards 
be at least 1000 feet apart the new law had the effect of 
preventing omni from putting up signs 
the 4th circuit court said the supreme court has granted cities 
a broad exemption from federal antitrust law when they enact 
anticompetitive rules in accord with state policies 
but the appeals court said the exemption does not permit the 
type of behavior engaged in by columbia officials 
sufficient evidence supports the jurys finding that there was 
a conspiracy between the city and columbia outdoor advertising 
the appeals court said the city was participating in the 
conspiracy solely for the purposes of restraint of trade and 
monopolization 
the appeals court said the city is immune from paying damages 
because of a federal law that exempts local governments from such 
awards 
in the appeal acted on today lawyers for the city and columbia 
outdoor advertising said the company engaged in wholly legitimate 
and successful lobbying of city officials to restrict outdoor 
advertising in the city 
the case is city of columbia vs omni outdoor advertising 
891671 
</TEXT>
