gubernatorial nomination in massachusetts 
the university argued that evidence of silbers alleged sexism 
should not have been presented to a federal jury that awarded ms 
brown 200000 
a judge added 15000 to compensate ms brown for emotional 
distress and ordered the university to reinstate her with lifetime 
tenure 
ms brown currently is teaching at providence university in 
rhode island where she has received tenure she said she would 
return to boston university if the university lost its supreme 
court appeal in the decadelong dispute 
ms brown had been teaching at bu for six years when she became 
eligible for tenure in 1979 
an english department committee voted 220 that she receive 
tenure and its recommendation was supported 92 by a university 
committee 
but silber opposed tenure and recommended instead that ms brown 
remain on probation for three more years 
silber relied in part on a report by the university provost 
questioning ms browns scholarly credentials 
she had published a book of criticism on jane austens novels 
that generally was well reviewed by other scholars but the provost 
said the university should await further evidence of ms browns 
abilities before awarding tenure 
after ms brown rejected the offer of three more years on 
probation the university board of trustees denied her tenure 
when her lawsuit reached a trial evidence was introduced of 
silbers alleged sexism 
it included a remark he made describing the english department 
as a damn matriarchy at a time when the department was headed 
by a woman and included six female and 20 male faculty members 
silber also had told another woman on the faculty that she 
should not be worried about job security since your husband is a 
parachute an apparent reference to the fact her husband was 
employed 
the jury also heard a portion of an old speech by silber in 
which he lamented the lack of parental supervision in families in 
which both husbands and wives work outside the home 
the 1st us circuit court of appeals in ruling last year for 
ms brown refused to order a new trial in which the silber remarks 
would be excluded 
the appeals court also rejected the universitys arguments that 
awarding ms brown a lifetime job interfered with its academic 
freedom 
academic freedom does not include the freedom to discriminate 
against tenure candidates on the basis of sex or other 
impermissible grounds the appeals court said awarding ms 
brown tenure is the only way to provide her the most complete 
relief possible 
the american council on education representing some 1500 
colleges and universities supported the universitys appeal 
the american association of university professors urged the high 
court to reject the appeal 
the case is boston university vs brown 891680 
</TEXT>
