<TEXT>
the supreme court today left intact the 
conviction and 250 fine of a man cited for preaching too loudly 
outside a hagerstown md abortion clinic 
the justices without comment refused to hear arguments that 
the state law used to prosecute jerry wayne eanes violates 
freespeech rights 
marylands highest court rejected those arguments by a 43 vote 
last february 
the challenged state law makes it a crime to disturb the peace 
in public places by making loud and unseemly noises 
eanes was arrested outside the hagerstown reproductive clinic on 
may 18 1988 while preaching on the city sidewalk outside the 
clinic 
the police officer who arrested eanes had previously asked him 
to lower his voice and said eanes continued to shout 
there was testimony that eanes could be heard over a block away 
although eanes was arrested during business hours on a busy 
downtown street the neighborhood has several residential apartment 
buildings police received complaints from residents about the 
loudness of eanes voice but not about his message 
eanes did not try to restrain anyone who entered or left the 
abortion clinic he did not try to block access to the clinic 
threaten anyone trespass on private property or use profanity 
a day before his arrest eanes had been acquitted in the 
washington county circuit court for allegedly making loud and 
unseemly noises in front of the same abortion clinic on in july 
1987 eanes had not returned to the clinic until his acquittal 
judge frederick c wright iii found eanes guilty of willfully 
disturbing the peace and tranquility of that particular 
neighborhood on may 18 by making loud and otherwise unacceptable 
noises 
the judge said eanes loud preaching was improper under the 
circumstances 
the maryland court of appeals last february upheld the 
misdemeanor conviction ruling that the law was aimed at the manner 
of eanes communication not its content 
judge wright properly balanced eanes first amendment rights 
against a substantial public interest protected by a narrowly 
drawn contentneutral regulation the state court said 
the three dissenting judges voted to overturn eanes conviction 
eanes was entitled to deliver an unamplified speech on the 
topic of abortion from a public sidewalk in downtown hagerstown 
during the late morning the dissenters said to punish as 
criminal the making of the speech purportedly because it was too 
loud distorts both the statute and our basic constitutional 
guarantees 
the case is eanes vs maryland 891745 
