<TEXT>
india and pakistan agreed today to hold 
talks to try to ease the threat of war over the disputed northern 
region of kashmir 
an indian government spokesman said top officials of the nations 
will meet early next month but that the date and location had not 
been decided the foreign ministry spokesman could not be 
indentified under briefing rules 
in islamabad pakistans foreign secretary tanvir ahmed khan 
confirmed the proposed meeting i think this is a welcome 
development he said this could be a good beginning 
a dispute over the kashmir valley has brought the neighbors 
close to their fourth war since they gained independence from 
britain in 1947 
india and pakistan both claim kashmir a predominately moslem 
state that joined mainly hindu india when britain partitioned the 
subcontinent along religious lines 
the territory is divided between the nations by a ceasefire 
line and the armies of both countries have massed troops and 
artillery along the border 
talk of war has disturbed many countries because both nations 
are believed to possess nuclear weapons technology india exploded 
an atomic device in 1974 two of the three previous indiapakistan 
wars fought in 1948 and 1965 have been over kashmir both were 
won by india 
india accuses pakistan of arming and training moslem kashmiri 
militants who are fighting for independence from india 
pakistan denies the charges however islamabad has often said 
it supports the kashmiri secession calling it a movement for 
selfdetermination 
india launched a crackdown on the separatist movement on jan 
20 since then more than 550 people have died in the valley 
mostly independence activists or their supporters 
in may a deputy us national security adviser robert gates 
traveled to pakistan and india to urge them to open talks western 
diplomats in new delhi today credited the gates visit and soviet 
pressure with helping to defuse the situation slightly 
