<TEXT>
an environmental group called on consumers 
today to boycott products containing a chemical used in such items 
as hornet sprays and art supplies which it said is harming earths 
ozone layer 
the natural resources defense council also accused the bush 
administration of waffling in its position on an international 
agreement designed to curb production of the chemical 
111trichloroethane 
the nrdc said approximately 724 million pounds of the chemical 
known as 111 for short were produced in the united states in 
1988 
david doniger an attorney with the group said 90 percent of 
the substance is used in industry where it is an ingredient of 
solvents used to clean electronic and metal parts 
among consumer goods which contain the chemical the nrdc said 
are some of the varnishes and fixatives marketed by m grumbacher 
inc the art supply firm 
godfrey chambers technical services manager for grumbacher 
said by telephone from the firms headquarters in cranbury nj 
that the company has eliminated 111 from some of its products and 
is hoping to get it eliminated from the ones listed 
chambers said the products damar varnish myston retouch 
varnish and tuffilm fixative are manufactured by a supplier and 
purchased by grumbacher for resale 
the person we purchase it from is continuing research in this 
matter to try and eliminate it he said 
formerly more of our aerosols did contain it but through the 
process of research we have been able to eliminate it he said 
it is a concern of the industry at large chambers said 
doniger said substitutes are available for 111 in most of its 
industrial and consumer uses 
we recommend that consumers avoid buying products which 
contain 111trichloroethane or any other substance which 
contributes to the destruction of the stratospheric ozone layer 
the council said for most applications there are alternative 
products on the market that serve the same purpose 
the nrdc listed 141 products but said there are more the ones 
listed included hair sprays spot removers solvents and cleaners 
furniture polish water repellents insecticides automotive 
products and other office and household items 
doniger said he will be pressing for phasing out of 111 when 
representatives of more than 70 nations gather in london wednesday 
under sponsorship of the united nations environmental program to 
consider revisions to an international agreement on the ozone layer 
the us delegation is still waffling somewhere between a 25 
percent rollback and a 100 percent phaseout by 2000 he said 
indications are that the european community and japan and now 
the united states are balking at going farther than 50 percent 
he added 
some environmentalists say manmade chemicals are eating away the 
earths protective ozone shield allowing more ultraviolet rays to 
reach the planets surface they contend this increases the risk of 
skin cancer cataract formation and disruption of the environment 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

