<DOCNO> AP900618-0071 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the heirs of the communist party have won 
control of parliament in bulgarias first free elections in 58 
years but unofficial results today showed the capital firmly in 
opposition hands 
bulgarias ruling socialists are the only reform communists to 
hold onto power in an eastern europe where authoritarian rule gave 
way to popular elections this year after decades of soviet 
domination 
premier andrei lukanov today said he was confident he could form 
a government with broad support he said he was encouraged by the 
main opposition coalitions support for a government of 
nonpartisan administrators 
members of bulgarias communist party formed the socialist party 
and staterun sofia radio said unofficial final results showed the 
socialists won 39 of the 81 seats at stake in sundays runoffs 
that would give them them a total of 211 seats in the 400member 
parliament 
the main opposition alliance the union of democratic forces 
won 37 seats for a total of 144 the radio said among those were 
six more seats in sofia to give the alliance 24 of the capitals 26 
seats unofficial counts showed 
the opposition in this country of 9 million gets much of its 
backing from the urban intelligensia while the socialists are seen 
as a force for stability in the balkan countrys more conservative 
countryside 
the agrarian party a once docile ally of the communists won 16 
seats in the june 10 first round and had no candidates in the 
runoff other smaller opposition groups and independents won a 
total of six seats 
official results were expected tuesday 
noncommunists have triumphed in nationwide elections in east 
germany czechoslovakia hungary and romania although the party 
that swept last months balloting in romania has many former 
communists in its leadership 
the communists have been a strong political force in bulgaria 
for nearly a century and as the socialist party the name they took 
in april have essentially maintained political control of small 
towns and villages 
opposition leaders have accused the socialists of using 
intimidation and fraud to secure votes 
foreign observers say they have not noted significant 
irregularities and sundays voting appeared to proceed smoothly at 
most polling sites however state television reported some 
irregularities including illegal canvassing 
dimiter ivanov an activist from the association for fair 
elections said that in some cases the number of people voting 
exceeded the number of people registered in the respective 
precincts 
outside a polling station in the town of stanke dimitrov about 
40 miles south of sofia a young soldier who refused to give his 
name said he voted for the socialists because i want security i 
am scared of the udf 
the opposition was only nascent when reform communists ousted 
longtime communist strongman todor zhivkov in november and had 
wanted the elections postponed until the fall to give it more time 
to organize 
shortly before the polls closed state television said 75 
percent of the eligible voters had cast ballots in the first first 
round 91 percent voted 
the socialists have proposed a coalition government of national 
unity but the union of democratic forces has resisted 
the socialist leader alexander lilov said in an interview 
published sunday in the party daily duma that if the opposition 
refuses to join a coalition his party will approach respected 
personalities to form a government of experts and 
professionals 
petar beron a union of democratic forces leader said today 
that his 16party coalition would favor such a government if it 
were temporary such a government is usually a caretaker 
government but it cannot rule the country for very long 
the chief task of the new government will be tackling the 
countrys 10 billion foreign debt rising inflation and consumer 
goods shortages while gearing the economy toward capitalism 
the union of democratic forces favors sweeping private ownership 
and privatization of agriculture 
the socialists would prefer to leave some industry 
governmentrun for the time being and are vague on the future 
status of farming which is currently governmentowned or 
cooperative 
</TEXT>
