<TEXT>
a wisconsin experiment aimed at keeping 
welfare children in school was praised monday as a longterm 
investment in youth and at the same time criticized as cruel and 
ineffective 
the federal government is interested enough in the learnfare 
concept which cuts off welfare payments to families whose 
teenagers miss class to authorize an expansion supporters 
acknowledged it is too early to judge whether the program begun in 
1987 has worked 
patricia a goodrich secretary of the wisconsin department of 
health and social services told a senate finance subcommittee 
hearing that learnfare provides the unique opportunity to have a 
direct and positive influence on the futures of our children and 
through them the future of our state and nation 
learnfare covers 27000 wisconsin teenagers whose parents 
receive aid to families with dependent children and 92 percent 
of those students are meeting the programs attendance 
requirements ms goodrich said 
if a teenager whose parents receive welfare has more than two 
unexcused absences in a month the familys welfare payment is cut 
by the amount normally included for the teenagers needs 
carol croce executive director of the wisconsin nutrition 
project said learnfare exacerbates family situations already 
strained by poverty and the pressures of single parenting 
grants reduced by learnfare sanctions have resulted in 
evictions and utility shutoffs and have forced some families into 
emergency shelters ms croce told the subcommittee it has had 
a perverse and destructive effect on family structure by giving 
teens unwarranted control over the familys income 
even with the program she added we still dont know why 
these teens are absent from school 
backers of the program say that requiring teenagers to stay in 
school will help break the cycle of poverty and prepare them for 
better jobs 
the us department of health and human services recently 
approved wisconsins proposal to expand the program to cover 
younger children however families of these children will not face 
a reduction in their welfare payments so long as parents cooperate 
with learnfare case workers 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

