<TEXT>
an army private who was demoted and thrown out 
of the service after his rifle was stolen will receive an honorable 
discharge and back pay the service said today 
the action involves pfc james griffin iii of fort lauderdale 
fla whose case was the subject of a 60 minutes television 
report last month 
griffin was serving with task force arriba in san lorenzo 
honduras in march 1989 when he was charged with loss of his rifle 
the enlisted man contended that the rifle had been stolen but his 
us superiors turned him over to honduran authorities for 
interrogation 
he was released 18 hours later after undergoing brutal 
questioning and was eventually returned to fort bragg nc where 
five months later he was thrown out of the army 
the army decision to reverse its earlier action was taken by the 
army board for the correction of military records according to 
army spokesman maj joe allred it calls for giving griffin an 
honorable discharge dated june 8 1990 restoration to the rank of 
private first class and e3 pay grade and lifting a ban on his 
reenlistment 
allred said griffin will receive full back pay and allowances 
for the period covering his initial discharge date of sept 19 
1989 to june 8 1990 but that the exact amount has not yet been 
determined 
the army action came after the pentagons inspector general 
recommended that griffin receive the honorable discharge 
the inspector general said griffin had been the victim of a ruse 
devised to obtain information about the lost weapon four army 
officers stationed in honduras with griffin were involved in the 
affair three were given letters of reprimand while a fourth 
received verbal counseling 
</TEXT>
