<TEXT>
the supreme court today said it will decide 
the effective date for a 1986 federal law setting tough new minimum 
sentences for drug violations 
at issue is whether the laws penalty provisions took effect in 
1986 or 1987 
the court agreed to hear an appeal by moshe gozlonperetz who 
was convicted in new jersey of conspiracy to distribute heroin and 
related offenses and was sentenced to 15 years in prison plus five 
years of supervised release after he completes his term he also 
was fined 200000 
gozlonperetz was caught in a drug enforcement administration 
sting when he sold heroin to a federal agent in atlantic city in 
february 1987 
gozlonperetz said he should not be subject to the fiveyear 
supervised release provisions of the 1986 law because those 
provisions did not become effective until nov 1 1987 after the 
commission of the crime 
the 3rd us circuit court of appeals said the penalty 
provisions of the law took effect oct 27 1986 the date the law 
was enacted 
the case is gozlonperetz vs us 897370 
