<TEXT>
secretary of state james a baker iii 
met today with five central american presidents and discussed how 
to coordinate us and other foreign aid to build the regions 
economies 
he arrived in antigua on sunday night to attend the close of the 
threeday meeting in which the central american leaders agreed to 
form a central american economic community to fight poverty 
officials said baker outlined a plan for coordinating aid trade 
and investment in central america from a variety of nations and 
organizations 
the idea is based on the model adopted by a group of 24 
developed nations for helping poland and hungary make the 
transition to freemarket democracies 
bakers proposal is seen as a clear affirmation of us 
intentions to maintain its traditional influence in the region 
after a breakfast meeting with baker president rafael callejas 
of honduras told a joint news conference the central american 
leaders fully expect the us proposal to mean additional aid for 
the region but that no specific sums nor the touchy issue of who 
would manage the program had been discussed 
the united states has been saying it wants to manage the 
program but the regions leaders have indicated they want to 
manage it themselves or have the final decision on who would run it 
we didnt talk about sums or structures callejas said 
salvadoran president alfredo cristiani said there will be more 
detailed discussions at the next central american summit to be 
held sometime within the next three months in costa rica 
he said baker had committed the united states to further talks 
with the donor countries among the industrialized nations expected 
to provide central america with aid are japan canada and the 
european economic community 
baker also was to hold individual meetings with each of the 
presidents today 
the presidents all elected civilians agreed in two accords 
sunday night to try to mesh the regions economies they pledged 
coordinated action on foreign trade and debt on rebuilding 
infrastructures on agricultural and industrial policy and 
attracting investment 
costa rican president rafael calderon said the region deeply 
scarred by a decade of civil strife needs international support 
we dont extend our hand to ask for charity calderon said 
but we say to you here are the central american people who are 
willing to give their labor their effort and their dedication but 
who also need the friendly hand of the developing world 
callejas has said central america needs at least 25 billion in 
aid over the next three years to begin rebuilding 
the task will be immense according to a study by the un 
economic commission for latin america and the caribbean the 
regional gross domestic product has fallen 20 percent since 1978 
the summit marked a turning point for central america which has 
suffered decades of dictatorship revolution and political social 
and economic crisis 
war and violence are an act of human cruelty but poverty is 
an act of human abandonment we must confront the presidents of 
guatemala el salvador nicaragua honduras and costa rica said in 
their accords 
violence is a part of our history we will not forget but we 
must not repeat now we set out on other roads 
the antigua meeting was the eighth central american summit but 
the first to deal almost exclusively with economic issues 
the presidents hope to repeat the success of the nobel 
prizewinning regional peace plan in nicaragua the plan helped 
end the war and brought elections that ousted central americas 
only leftist government 
the peace plan was also the catalyst for peace talks now under 
way between leftist rebels and the governments of el salvador and 
guatemala 
the economic accords reflect a search for solutions acceptable 
to the regions powerful vested interests 
attempts to redistribute wealth have cost tens of thousands of 
lives and the development agenda for the 1990s aims at generating 
more wealth instead of at redistribution 
nicaraguan president violeta barrios de chamorro and costa rican 
president calderon both elected this year signed the plan as 
firsttime participants in a regional summit 
signing for guatemala was president vinicio cerezo 
panamanian president guillermo endara signed as an invited 
observer 
