<TEXT>
the state of florida will test the new 
legal climate for abortion restrictions this week when it asks a 
federal judge for more authority to regulate abortion clinics 
eight years ago us district judge jose gonzalez issued a 
ruling that limited regulation of private abortion clinics to four 
areas on tuesday gonzalez is to hear testimony and arguments in 
his fort lauderdale courtroom over proposed changes in that 
injunction 
state officials hope the result will be a ruling that gives them 
broader powers to regulate sanitation and other aspects of abortion 
clinic operations abortion rights activists hope gonzalez will 
continue to give the state only limited authority over the clinics 
this is the second highprofile case in a month for gonzalez 
who on june 6 declared an album by the rap group 2 live crew to be 
obscene 
in the abortion case the state has argued that current rules of 
floridas department of health and rehabilitative services arent 
strong enough to guarantee public health and safety 
women served by abortion clinics are now treated as 
secondclass citizens in comparison to similar patients at birthing 
centers and ambulatory surgical centers the motion says 
