<TEXT>
the supreme court said today it will use the 
case of an eye surgeon denied staff privileges at a los angeles 
hospital to study the scope of a key federal antitrust law 
the justices agreed to hear an appeal by the hospital seeking to 
dismiss the doctors antitrust suit a ruling is not expected until 
next year 
the case stems from a dispute between dr simon pinhas and 
midway hospital medical center which is owned by summit health ltd 
pinhas a member of midways staff since 1981 protested in 1986 
a hospital requirement that an assistant surgeon be present for the 
performance of eye surgery 
medicare reimbursement for assistant eye surgeons was 
discontinued in 1986 and pinhas said requiring him to have an 
assistant present when he performed operations would cost him 
60000 a year 
the hospital refused to abolish the assistant surgeon 
requirement but offered pinhas what he called a sham contract 
promising to pay him 60000 a year for nonexistent consulting 
services 
pinhas refused to sign the contract or to return it to hospital 
officials 
he said that prompted hospital administrators to suspend his 
staff privileges at midway 
he then sued accusing hospital officials of engaging in an 
anticompetitive conspiracy forbidden by the sherman antitrust act 
he said the officials boycotted his practice and prevented his 
continued competition in the marketplace 
a federal judge threw out the suit but it was reinstated last 
year by the 9th us circuit court of appeals 
at issue is whether there is enough of a connection with 
interstate commerce to invoke the sherman antitrust act 
the 9th circuit court said pinhas need only prove that 
peerreview proceedings have an effect on interstate commerce a 
fact that can hardly be disputed the proceedings affect the entire 
staff at midway and thus affect the hospitals interstate 
commerce 
hospital officials said pinhas should be required to show that 
the hospitals alleged anticompetitive conduct affects interstate 
commerce not merely that the hospital is engaged in interstate 
commerce 
the california association of hospitals and health systems 
supported midways appeal 
the case is summith health ltd vs pinhas 891679 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

