<DOCNO> AP900618-0115 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
police may ask suspected drunken drivers most 
routine questions and videotape their answers without warning them 
of their rights the supreme court ruled monday 
the 81 ruling in a pennsylvania case means slurred responses to 
questions about age height and weight may be used to convict 
motorists who have not been told they have a right to a lawyer and 
to remain silent 
but the court said police may not ask a suspect more difficult 
questions for example the date of the drivers sixth birthday 
without giving socalled miranda warnings 
justice william j brennan writing for the court said 
responses to questions about height weight and similar 
biographical data are admissible because the questions fall 
within a routine booking question exception which exempts them 
from mirandas coverage 
the court ordered a state court to consider reinstating the 
drunkendriving conviction of inocencio muniz 
it was the second time in a week the court upheld police tactics 
to fight drunken driving the court ruled last week that sobriety 
checkpoints dont violate motorists rights 
an upper allen township pa policeman noticed munizs car 
stopped by the side of the road nov 30 1986 with the motor 
running 
the officer said he smelled alcohol on munizs breath and that 
the mans eyes were glazed and bloodshot the officer said he told 
muniz not to drive until he was in a condition to operate the car 
safely but muniz drove off as the officer returned to his patrol 
car 
the patrolman pursued muniz ordered him to stop and told him to 
perform some sobriety tests muniz failed all the tests 
the officer took muniz to a police station where the motorist 
was videotaped answering questions about his name address height 
weight eye color date of birth age and date of his sixth 
birthday 
only after those responses was muniz given the miranda warnings 
muniz convicted previously of drunken driving was convicted 
again and sentenced to 45 days to 23 months in prison 
the supreme court action monday reversed a pennsylvania appeals 
court ruling that threw out the latter conviction in 1988 
brennan said permitting the judge who convicted muniz to hear 
his slurred responses did not violate munizs privilege against 
selfincrimination but brennan said asking muniz to state the date 
of his sixth birthday falls into a different category 
muniz was left with the choice of incriminating himself by 
admitting that he did not then know the date of his sixth birthday 
or answering untruthfully by reporting a date that he did not 
believe to be accurate brennan said 
he said that unlike munizs responses to the other questions 
the suspects answer to the sixthbirthday question was 
incriminating because of its content not just because of the 
delivery 
four justices said they would permit the sixthbirthday question 
as well they are chief justice william h rehnquist and justices 
byron r white harry a blackmun and john paul stevens 
justice thurgood marshall dissented voting to bar munizs 
conviction 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

