<TEXT>
fourteen scientists from the united states and 
the soviet union will spend the summer camping in the backcountry 
of siberia to study climate changes the agriculture department 
said monday 
the joint team will then collect similar information in the 
united states officials said the objective is to examine the 
possible effects of climate change on forests 
the project is sponsored by the departments forest service and 
moscows state forest committee and organized by the institute for 
resource management a nonprofit environmental group founded by 
actor robert redford 
field research will be coordinated by the university of 
california at santa barbara under the direction of daniel b botkin 
and the soviet unions allunion scientific research center of the 
state forest committee directed by anatoly z shvidenko 
patricia kearney acting assistant secretary for natural 
resources and environment said in a statement that the venture is 
a unique opportunity to work cooperatively with the soviet 
union toward improved management of natural resources 
kearney and terrell minger president of the institute are in 
moscow attending a climate change workshop to coordinate procedures 
and plans for the project 
the soviet research sites are in yakutsk in eastern siberia 
and in the komi region in western russia 
after two months the team will collect similar information at 
us sites in caribou creek alaska appoximately 40 miles north of 
fairbanks and the boundary waters canoe area in the superior 
national forest minnesota 
the department did not name the us scientists participating in 
the joint research project 
