<TEXT>
bulgaria on monday became the first east 
european nation to freely elect a parliament dominated by the 
former communist party opting for a slow changeover to a market 
economy 
while bulgarias first free elections in 58 years ends the 
communists rubberstamp domination of politics it also ensures a 
sizeable opposition with enough votes to veto constitutional 
proposals 
we will resolutely move in the direction of a democratic 
european leftist party premier andrei lukanov said expressing 
confidence he could form a government of consensus 
but the leader of the main opposition alliance rejected any deal 
with the former communists 
according to official results of sundays runoff elections the 
ruling socialist party which until april was the communist party 
clinched an absolute majority with 211 seats in the 400seat 
parliament 
the main opposition union of democratic forces udf a 16party 
alliance captured 144 seats the ethnic turkish rights and 
freedoms movement won 23 seats and the mainstream agrarian party 
16 smaller parties and independents won six seats 
the capital sofia going against the nationwide trend voted 
overwhelmingly for the opposition electing udf candidates for 24 
of 26 available seats 
analysts say the socialists represent stability for many who 
feared the loss of jobs and social upheaval in a quick switch to 
private ownership favored by the udf the socialists favor leaving 
some industry staterun for now 
bulgaria has a nearly centuryold communist tradition more 
deeply rooted than elsewhere in eastern europe and the current 
socialist leadership scored points for ousting hardliner todor 
zhivkov in november and initiating gradual reforms 
the socialist leaders were also seen as more charismatic and 
their campaign more professional than the sevenmonthold udf 
apart from bulgaria noncommunist parties have triumphed in 
this years round of national elections in east germany 
czechoslovakia and hungary following last years regional 
revolutions in romania the national salvation front that won a 
landslide victory includes many excommunists 
the new government must tackle the countrys 10 billion foreign 
debt rising inflation and shortages of basic goods the newly 
elected unicameral grand national assembly must also write a 
constitution which requires twothirds approval for adoption 
victorious socialist party leaders many carrying red 
carnations were applauded and kissed by cheering supporters 
in an interview with the associated press lukanov reiterated 
his refusal to head a cabinet composed only of members of his own 
socialist party 
he welcomed remarks made by udf chairman zhelyu zhelev about the 
possibility of what lukanov described as a government of 
responsible and competent personalities 
this does not mean i accept his idea i note with great 
interest his recognition that a government if it is to be 
successful has to be supported by all political forces lukanov 
declared 
but zhelev told the ap the udf would not be part of a socialist 
government though another senior udf official petar beron said a 
government of experts remained a possible consideration 
the udf coordinating council the alliances executive organ 
was scheduled to meet tuesday to hammer out a joint stand and 
informed sources said heated discussions were expected 
zhelev described the outcome of the elections means we are a 
strong constructive opposition and the bsp socialists will be a 
weak oneparty government 
he said the idea of a government of nonpolitical professionals 
was made when there was a real likelihood of a hung parliament 
in such a situation as is usual in theory and practice in the 
world they have to form their own government zhelev explained 
if they dont like that they can form a government of experts of 
their own but we will not be part of it 
lukanov 51 a multilingual economics expert suggested a split 
in his party possibly at a new party congress this fall and in 
the udf could change bulgarias political landscape and ensure 
ultimate stability 
the present distribution of forces is rather artificial the 
premier noted it hides the diversity of views nuances 
ideologies 
the socialists gained 172 seats in firstround voting june 10 
and needed to capture only 29 of the 81 seats at stake in sundays 
runoff to win a majority 
according to the official results released by the central 
electoral commission the socialists won 39 and the udf won 37 the 
remainder went to independents and smaller parties 
state television reported some voting irregularities in the 
runoff dimiter ivanov an activist from the association of fair 
elections said in some cases the number of people voting exceeded 
the number of people registered in the respective precincts 
</TEXT>
