<TEXT>
the national transportation safety board said 
monday that federal authorities arent doing enough to protect 
airliners from dangerous winds during takeoff and landing at major 
airports 
the board which has no regulatory power recommended that the 
federal aviation administration buy additional groundbased 
equipment to warn planes of sudden changes of wind speed and 
direction known as windshear 
at least eight passenger plane accidents in the last 17 years 
have been blamed at least in part on wind hazards 
the fourmember board noted that the faa has taken several steps 
to protect airplanes against windshear including future required 
installation of detection equipment aboard airliners 
however the board believes that additional actions are 
required by the faa for maximum protection against this hazard in 
the national airspace system said a board announcement 
board recommendations were outlined in a 11page letter to faa 
administrator james busey 
the board called for appointment of an faa meteorologist at 
major airports and purchase of sophisticated weather radar systems 
at all airports determined to be susceptible to lowaltitude 
windshear conditions 
the invisible hazard which occurs under thunderstorms or in 
connection with weather fronts is considered most dangerous near 
the ground at airports where it can affect planes during takeoff or 
landing 
the board also called for interim improvements at airports where 
installation of windshear detection equipment might take some time 
to install or where the weather radar systems arent planned 
the board said its recommendations were based on a review of 
more than 40 safety recommendations it has issued to the faa over 
the past 16 years 
the safety board which operates independently from the faa or 
the transportation department investigates accidents and regularly 
makes recommendations for safety improvements in transportation 
systems it gave the faa 90 days to respond 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

