<TEXT>
as hurricane season begins 
burnedout light bulbs have forced storm specialists to rely on 
one instead of two highorbit weather satellites for the fifth 
time in seven years 
only one highorbit us weather satellite is watching us 
coastlines meaning that this year again hurricane specialists 
wont get a full picture of the atlantic oceans hurricane breeding 
grounds 
efforts to keep two satellites going havent worked so the 
working one being nudged into hurricaneseason position at a mere 
mph to save fuel will have to get through the 1991 season alone 
if this satellite goes 7 fails like three predecessors 
forecasters lose one of their best tools for monitoring everything 
from hurricanes threatening the east coast to typhoons off hawaii 
the problem is the satellites 1000 light bulbs which create 
the photographic images forecasters use to watch weather systems 
only one satellite has outlived its fiveyear design life before 
its light bulbs burned out and then by just seven months two 
others lasted only three years before their 1000 light bulbs 
failed 
a fourth satellite was lost in 1986 when the delta rocket 
carrying it had to be destroyed in flight 
to solve the light bulb problem goes 7 also was equipped with 
lightemitting diodes similar to whats used in calculators 
that should be more durable said gary davis noaas chief of 
satellite operations 
the geostationary operational environmental satellite placed in 
orbit 22300 miles above earth has a speed matching earths 
rotation so it appears parked above a particular spot 
when two goes satellites work in tandem forecasters can see 
from the coast of africa out into the pacific ocean beyond the 
hawaiian islands but noaa has had trouble keeping two working at 
once 
the national oceanic and atmospheric administration says the 50 
million goes 7 is the sturdiest of its series 
for two years goes 7 has bounced back and forth across the sky 
spending the hurricane season at 98 degrees longitude above the 
galapagos islands and the rest of the year 611 miles to the west 
at 108 degrees longitude where theres a better view of the 
pacific ocean beyond the hawaiian islands 
goes 7 should be in hurricane position by aug 21 the season 
runs june 1 to nov 30 but historically the worst storms are born 
in september and october 
the satellites position is a compromise goes 7 will not be 
able to see all the way to the cape verde islands off the coast of 
africa where killer hurricanes tend to form but if it was moved 
farther east it couldnt be used to monitor pacific ocean storms 
if goes 7 fails the national hurricane center still will be 
able to get pictures four times a day from two polarorbiting 
weather satellites and as a storm approaches land 
hurricanehunter airplanes could provide updates 
goes has a tremendous public relations value lawrence said 
all the news programs show the satellite pictures its such an 
excellent way to get people to respond to the threat he said 
next summer noaa plans to launch the first of a new generation 
of more powerful satellites called goes next but that satellite 
wont be ready for hurricane duty until 1992 
ground controllers hope they can keep goes 7s fuel burning 
slowly enough to keep its lights on until both goes next satellites 
are up and running 
