<TEXT>
the us supreme court on monday let stand a 
decision that granted a lifetime professorship to a woman whose 
sexual bias lawsuit alleged that boston university president john 
silber harbored sexist attitudes 
the court without comment rejected arguments that the lower 
court decision interfered with the schools academic freedom the 
decision required the university to grant tenure to julia prewitt 
brown 
i am glad that the supreme court has affirmed the longstanding 
authority of college faculties to judge scholarship and teaching 
an authority that has been undermined of late by the impositions of 
college administrators ms brown said in a statement released by 
her attorney 
ms brown who now teaches at providence college intends to 
return to boston university said dahlia rudavsky her lawyer 
she wants to go back now that were at a logical place between 
semesters shell be back soon 
ms brown had been teaching at boston for six years when she 
became eligible for tenure in 1979 an english department committee 
voted 220 that she receive tenure and its recommendation was 
supported 92 by a university committee 
silber opposed tenure and recommended instead that she remain on 
probation for three more years silber relied in part on a report 
by the university provost questioning ms browns scholarly 
credentials 
silber on monday said the issue was settled and he wished ms 
brown all the best 
he also defended himself against accusations that he was biased 
against women saying that 25 percent of the fulltime faculty at 
boston university are women and that 28 percent of the women have 
tenure figures that compare favorably with many other universities 
silber is on leave from the university to run for governor of 
massachusetts as a democrat his campaign spokeswoman michal 
regunberg said she was not familiar with the supreme court action 
and could not comment 
ms brown had published a book of criticism on jane austens 
novels that generally was well reviewed by other scholars but the 
provost said the university should await further evidence of ms 
browns abilities before awarding tenure 
after ms brown rejected the offer of three more years on 
probation the university board of trustees denied her tenure 
the university argued that evidence of silbers alleged sexism 
should not have been presented to a federal jury that awarded ms 
brown 200000 a judge added 15000 to compensate her for 
emotional distress and ordered the university to reinstate her 
with lifetime tenure 
as evidence of silbers alleged sexism ms brown introduced 
several statements made by silber 
one included a remark he made describing the english department 
as a damn matriarchy at a time when the department was headed 
by a woman and included six female and 20 male faculty members 
silber also had told another woman on the faculty that she 
should not be worried about job security since your husband is a 
parachute an apparent reference to the fact her husband was 
employed 
the jury also heard a portion of an old speech by silber in 
which he lamented the lack of parental supervision in families in 
which both husbands and wives work outside the home 
the 1st us circuit court of appeals in ruling last year for 
ms brown refused to order a new trial in which the silber remarks 
would be excluded 
the appeals court also rejected the universitys arguments that 
awarding ms brown a lifetime job interfered with its academic 
freedom 
academic freedom does not include the freedom to discriminate 
against tenure candidates on the basis of sex or other 
impermissible grounds the appeals court said awarding ms 
brown tenure is the only way to provide her the most complete 
relief possible 
