<DOCNO> AP900618-0160 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
federal safety investigators said monday 
current inspection methods might not detect a crack in a jet engine 
part like the one that caused last summers air crash in iowa that 
killed 112 people 
the national transportation safety board in formal 
recommendations to the federal aviation administration called for 
the faa and the engine manufacturer general electric co to 
develop new inspection methods to detect cracks before they reach 
dangerous size 
the middle tailmounted engine of a united air lines dc10 
exploded in flight on july 19 1989 cutting all hydraulic lines of 
the aircraft control system the pilots tried to make an emergency 
landing at sioux city iowa but the plane crashed during the 
attempt killing 111 or 296 people on board one of the injured 
later died 
according to the board the engine exploded because a crack in 
the inner bore of the firststage rotor disk grew so large that the 
rapidly spinning 270pound disk broke apart spewing shrapnellike 
pieces throughout the tail area of the aircraft the disk carries 
the 38 blades of the fan on the ge cf66 engine 
the flaw that led to the crack could have been detected if the 
final surface inspection by chemical etching had been done on the 
rotor in its final shape rather than an intermediate shape as was 
done the board concluded it recommended that the faa require this 
etching inspection on the final part shape of all rotating parts 
made of titanium 
the faa has 90 days to respond to the boards recommendations 
following the accident the faa ordered the six remaining disks 
made from the same ingot of titanium removed from service leaving 
55 made from the same raw material and 165 made before the 
manufacturing process was changed in 1971 
ultrasonic inspections were ordered for the remaining disks 
including those made by the new process 
but computer models developed by ge show that a surface crack in 
the forward area of the inner bore of the rotor disk could 
propagate from a size just below the level of detectability to a 
critical size in significantly fewer that 500 flights using one 
ultrasonic inspection method and the second method ordered to be 
used may not be any more capable of catching those cracks the 
board said 
the manufacturer calls on users to inspect rotor surfaces under 
ultraviolet light after a special wash whenever engines are taken 
apart the board said it was concerned that uniteds engine passed 
such an inspection 760 flight before the accident and was 
concerned that there are no requirements for such inspections at 
intervals based on expected crack growth rates 
the board has not determined why the crack was not discovered at 
the ultraviolet inspection 
the board said it concluded that the faas postcrash orders 
taken alone are inadequate to detect these potentially critical 
cracks it called on the faa to require an alternate inspection 
method such as the use of electrical eddy currents in the part 
being inspected 
the board also called on the faa to adopt for engines the 
assumption now used for aircraft structures when calculating 
inspection intervals not that the part is flawless originally 
but that it contains a flaw just below the level of detectability 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
