<TEXT>
a summary of developments in the news industry for the week of 
june 1118 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the soviet legislature on june 12 passed the 
countrys first law guaranteeing freedom of the press and creating 
broad rights for journalists and publishers 
the measure which was passed unanimously by the supreme soviet 
legislature also gives any citizen the right to start a media 
outlet 
the press and other mass media are free the law begins 
bluntly and censorship of the mass media is forbidden 
after president mikhail s gorbachev came to power in 1985 and 
introduced the policy of glasnost or openness political pressure 
on the soviet media began to lighten but there was still no legal 
protection from interference 
technically freedom of the press is guaranteed by a declaration 
in the soviet constitution but the new measure was the first law 
laying out detailed guarantees of press freedoms the tass news 
agency reported 
the law establishes procedures for creating media outlets and 
specifies journalists rights they include the right to attend 
meetings and be present at the scene of disasters the right to 
refuse to prepare reports that go against personal convictions and 
the right to hold interviews with officials 
the provision giving any individual the right to establish a 
media outlet created the sharpest debate in the supreme soviet 
tass reported 
the new law forbids publication of state secrets but tass said 
penalties would be imposed on the official who leaked them rather 
than the journalist who reported them 
it also forbids slander and use of the mass media to interfere 
in citizens private lives infringement on their honor and 
dignity 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
kansas citys new evening newspaper 
is making money after only a month of publication and will begin 
limited home delivery in the suburbs the tabloids owner said june 
14 
the kansas city evening news published monday through friday 
is selling an average of about 15000 copies at 50 cents each said 
owner steve rose 
thats about what i had projected for circulation i would 
have been very disappointed if we hadnt made money off of that 
said rose president of sun publications a familyowned string of 
suburban weekly newspapers 
he did not disclose how much money the newspaper was making 
when he launched the tabloid may 14 with startup costs he said 
were just 1 million rose estimated that a combination of small 
staff relatively small circulation and no home delivery would keep 
costs low 
but he said june 14 he will start limited home delivery in two 
suburbs overland park and leawood kan 
city ordinances prevent the evening news from being sold on 
street corners in those towns he said rather than go to court he 
decided to begin home delivery there later this month 
in other parts of the kansas city area the evening news will 
continue to be sold only at street corners newsracks and stores 
said rose who spoke in a telephone interview from san antonio 
where he was attending a newspaper conference 
analysts had predicted the paper would have a difficult time in 
a city dominated by a morning paper the kansas city star with 
circulation of about 300000 last march the kansas city times was 
merged with the kansas city star because of declining circulation 
rose said low costs would help him survive 
we could still sell down to as little as 10000 copies and 
make a profit he said of course i hope we dont do that 
the paper which averages about 32 pages a day contains mostly 
wire service reports on national and international news and sports 
it has four editorial employees and shares a building printing 
press and advertising and circulation staff with sun publications 
