<TEXT>
a hoaxer tricked the news media into running 
a bogus story about elizabeth taylor on june 10 by gaining access 
to messages left with a public relations companys answering 
service 
the story distributed worldwide by the associated press and 
united press international said miss taylor was romantically 
involved with a 23yearold man and had just undergone surgery 
it is a hoax said miss taylors publicist chen sam i 
have contacted miss taylors attorneys and we are going to conduct 
an investigation it is apparently somebody using my telephone 
service 
ms sams new york city public relations firm was the sole media 
link during miss taylors nineweek hospitalization for pneumonia 
at st johns hospital and health center in santa monica 
the sam organization discouraged reporters from calling st 
johns about miss taylor and instructed the hospitals public 
relations staff not to answer reporters questions under 
california privacy law hospitals must abide by the wishes of 
patients who dont want information released about them 
the ap office in los angeles had placed calls to the hospital 
and to chen sam and associates after receiving a message sunday 
from an ap affiliate in england the press association editors at 
the british domestic news agency had heard miss taylor had 
undergone another operation and wanted a story 
the hoaxer said miss taylor underwent an abdominal biopsy and 
was expected to be released from the hospital within two weeks on 
the arm of julian lee hobbs of lake orion mich described as miss 
taylors boyfriend 
the hospital spokeswoman was unavailable for comment when the 
reporter called new york he was connected to ms sams answering 
service and left a message 
a short time later a woman returned the call saying she was 
lisa flowers from chen sam and associates she then gave the 
reporter the bogus information about miss taylors romantic 
involvement and the surgery 
the hoaxer also provided the same story to upi and city news 
service a metropolitan los angeles wire service 
the ap reporter in an effort to verify the authenticity of the 
source later placed a second call to ms sams answering service 
leaving a message for lisa flowers the answering service operator 
accepted that message without question 
later an ap reporter placed a third call to ms sams answering 
service a woman identifying herself as ms sam returned that call 
and verified the identity of ms flowers and the story she had 
told 
ms sam said no one from her organization had talked to 
reporters she said a woman involved in the hoax had telephoned her 
answering service and was given the publicists messages after 
somehow providing proper coded identification to the switchboard 
it was all very cleverly done ms sam said it was done 
on a sunday when we werent around i cant understand how they got 
the code ive had to change the entire system here 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the venerable times of london has revised its 
victorianera style guide to include such brash and contemporary 
language as the title ms 
editor simon jenkins tried to break the news gently to readers 
of the 205yearold newspaper who tend to regard its 
eccentricities as a national treasure on the order of big ben 
the mirror that a newspaper holds up to the world is 
constantly smudged with jargon bad usage and verbosity jenkins 
wrote june 12 a style guide is a periodic cleansing of that 
mirror 
the times style guide introduced at the turn of the century 
was last revamped in the mid1960s 
there were regular updates but the guide remained terribly 
restrictive and quite victorian said literary editor philip 
howard who helped write the new one 
the old style guide was replete with arcane treasures such as 
the times singular spelling of mikhail s gorbachov its 
rendering of the soviet leaders name was based on its 
transliteration of the cyrillic letters 
our russian specialists know that our spelling is better but 
if the rest of the world spells it another way ours looks very 
odd howard said were right but were wrong 
so from now on its gorbachev 
under the old style the times referred to leonardo da vincis 
masterpiece as the monna lisa to show it was derived from 
madonna it will now be mona lisa 
from now on ms will be automatically used in times news 
columns for american women and for others if they request it 
the times is also dropping courtesy titles on first reference 
something certain to disappoint readers who enjoyed such prim 
designations as mr ringo starr 
on subsequent reference most people continue to get a title 
except criminals artists athletes and the long dead 
the new guide also has a blacklist words that slip into 
journalese as a form of obfuscation and circumlocution and 
gobbledygook howard said 
these include problem provision very issue accommodate 
crisis interesting and situation especially crisis 
situation and probe 
words like probe should be confined to stories about 
surgeons he said 
</TEXT>
