close votes because it will take the approval of twothirds of 
those voting in each branch to approve the amendment and send it on 
to the state legislatures three fourths of the states would have 
to approve to a flagburning ban into the constitution 
after the first court ruling on june 21 1989 the estimates 
were that an amendment would have cleared congress easily 
democratic leaders contained the issue and the political anger 
behind it by drafting a statute to ban flag desecration that put 
a flag vote on the record without a constitutional amendment 
theres no such option now that the supreme court has overturned 
that law 
opponents of a constitutional amendment are proposing a 
resolution condemning flag burning and declaring support for the 
bill of rights while it is has no binding effect it would offer a 
way to vote for the flag but not the amendment 
but thats not much political shelter on the real vote its 
yes or no and members of congress who plan to vote no already can 
envision the campaign commercials that will accuse them of catering 
to flagburning radicals 
