strains of mozart from the solisti 
new york chamber orchestra whistled across the rolling osage hills 
beneath a lodge where oilman frank phillips and humorist will 
rogers once spit tobacco juice on the front porch 
the outdoor concert at woolaroc wildlife preserve attracted a 
sellout crowd as it does every year more than 3000 people 
arrived two hours early to claim the best slaterock seats or to 
set up lawn chairs and blankets for a meal of buffalo burgers and 
beer 
we like to clash as long as everything is authentic and done 
in the best quality says nan buhlinger executive director of 
the ok mozart international festival 
quality is not questioned during the nineday festival which 
has grown so fast people are killing for tickets says ransom 
wilson a renowned flutist and artist director of the festival 
the solisti new york is complemented by robin sutherland 
pianist for the san francisco symphony frenchborn conductor 
catherine comet the boston chamber music society and several other 
nationally acclaimed artists from around the nation 
all of them set aside two weeks in june to come to this northern 
oklahoma town known more as the headquarters for phillips petroleum 
co than for aficionados of fine arts 
all you have to do is come once said sutherland who has 
been to every festival since it began in 1985 i feel sorry for 
those who cant come here or wont come here the high point of my 
year is to come here and collaborate with these people 
the festival could be considered unique because of the outdoor 
concert at woolaroc where artists don black and pink tshirts and 
concertgoers smell more of bug spray than perfumes 
but the concert hall in the bartlesville community center holds 
the key to the festival it was there in 1982 that wilson 
directed a symphony and fell in love with the acoustics 
sutherland who has known wilson since they attended the 
juilliard school in new york city said wilson asked him to come 
for the first ok mozart festival 
the first year was hard sutherland said i knew nothing 
about this place ransom said it was the coolest hall we know of 
so how does a city of 35000 come up with a concert hall that 
artists from boston new york and san francisco rave about 
its a matter of luck sutherland says there are 
accoustians who claim that different scientific factors determine 
the quality but if it comes down to science why are there so many 
rotten walls 
buhlinger said this years festival drew about 30000 from 31 
states because bartlesville doesnt have the activity of a 
metropolitan city she developed the festival showcase a gamut of 
displays and events that blend mozart with the heritage of oklahoma 
the showcase involves local residents something wilson said was 
instrumental in the rapid growth and national recognition the 
festival has achieved 
what makes this unique is there are two festivals at the same 
time wilson said its not just the concerts its the 
showcase events every day you get a real oklahoma flavor and the 
everyones participation is the key to the success 
if nothing else buhlinger said the mozart festival goes a long 
way in dispelling myths of oklahoma built on the days of cowboys 
and indians and the dust bowl 
i think most people are absolutely surprised she said 
everybody doesnt walk around here with straws in their teeth i 
think some people come here and expect to see wild horses running 
through the streets 
sutherland said all he needed was dinner in one residents home 
to remind him that bartlesville has plenty of culture 
these people may speak with a drawl but theyve got antiques 
in their homes from japan belgium he said phillips is a 
worldwide company its not like theyve never left their homes 
the charm of the smalltown mixed with an international 
corporation leads wilson to claim that all the smart people are 
here 
theres not another town like it that i have come across in 
the united states wilson said its got a population of 
35000 yet it has its own cultural institution they are educated 
people from all over the world and they demand culture 
and says string bassist carolyn davis of the solisti new york 
they cling to it 
its unique to have a town where everyone jumps on the 
bandwagon and is so enthusiastic said davis you dont need 
that much knowledge to understand the music and enjoy it 
i prefer playing for audiences with enthusiasm some sit on 
their hands and you dont get feedback so its not as special 
theres a certain camaraderie here 
 
