editors note at a time of growing uneasiness over japans 
encroachment into the us economy the japanese expatriate 
community is stressing volunteerism as the key to winning friends 
in america individuals and corporations alike are getting involved 
in local community service projects thats all the more remarkable 
because back home the concept of corporate social concern is rare 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
in america the gentleman from japan pursuing sogo shoku 
the career path to the executive suite is confronted with two 
conflicting challenges in the course of a long long day 
how to be a good corporate citizen in a host country where the 
polls and his own foreign minister assert that people feel more 
threatened by japans economic power than by the military might of 
the soviet union 
and how to maintain japanese culture within his own family 
circle constantly encircled by american lifestyles and values and 
the incomprehensible kids english that his children speak 
it is a puzzlement which could lead to ensei weariness of 
life because the day indeed is long 
in the new york metropolitan area where the japanese community 
is estimated at 60000 and the 736 commuter train out of hartsdale 
is known as the orient express a typical japanese executive 
will be at his desk by 830 am he stays at least until 730 pm 
which is the best time for phone calls from the shoguns at tokyo 
headquarters 
at noon in keeping with the new goodneighbor policy he may 
address a rotary club attend a united way meeting or teach a 
business course at a community college he may even join the 
serving line at an innercity soup kitchen 
when he arrives at his home in the suburbs late in the evening 
he may find his wife stuffing envelopes for the american heart 
association or teaching origami the ancient art of folding paper 
into fanciful animals to a group of neighbors 
before hitting the futon his sleeping mat he tries to coax the 
kids away from tv long enough to discuss japanese culture and maybe 
help them compose a haiku or two those exquisite snowflakes of 
poems written in three lines of 17 syllables 
on weekends he may umpire a little league game a most 
humbling experience good for the soul as a nippon steel 
executive admitted or join his son on a camping trip play in a 
company softball game or go on a chartered bus to the concord a 
jewish resort in the catskills for a round of golf which is so 
expensive in japan 
he worries about koroshi death from overwork sometimes 
diagnosed as harikari at the water cooler 
but these days he worries most about being a good corporate 
citizen in america 
at a time when japans 50 billion annual trade imbalance is 
increasing friction with the united states and a fortune magazine 
cover story warns that for too many americans the japanese have 
become the people its ok to hate the growing japanese 
expatriate community is anxiously stressing volunteerism as the 
key to understanding and friendship 
volunteerism is a significant element of life in the united 
states that we in the japanese community both as individuals and 
corporations must come to terms with urged hisao kondo 
president of mitsui usa in his preface to joining in a 
howto book on community involvement issued by the japanese chamber 
of commerce and industry in new york 
british investors actually control more of america but the 
japanese seem to be everywhere and into everything from 7eleven 
stores and mama leones restaurant to rockefeller center columbia 
pictures and cbs records 
it was the smiling elaborately courteous gentlemen from japan 
who plunked down 82 million for van goghs portrait of dr 
gachet then two days later 78 million for renoirs at the 
moulin de la galette 
they control eight of the worlds 10 largest banks own much of 
waikiki beach anne klein fashions tiffanys the arco plaza and 
riviera country club in los angeles and such landmark new york 
hotels as the algonquin the stanhope and the essex house they are 
backing several broadway shows and peddling americas bestselling 
car the honda accord 
they are buying up colorado ranches to market an overseas 
version of handmassaged kobe beef and even televisions latest 
primetime blockbuster americas funniest home videos is a 
spinoff from a tokyos fun with ken and kaito chan 
they are seen handing out checks on tv to winners of pga golf 
tournaments with names like the honda classic the nissan los 
angeles open and the isuzu kapalua international 
