<TEXT>
sue miller admits she made a huge false 
start on her new novel for hundreds of pages she wrote about a 
subject she knew would bore herself and readers as well a happy 
family 
it could have been a very happy book where the mother stays at 
home and is very happy with the three children miller said of 
family pictures 1995 harper and row in which a familys 
life is disrupted by the birth of an autistic child 
if the child had not been born autistic i wouldnt have 
written about the family people dont write books about happy 
families it is true that fiction focuses on hardship 
i think in some way or another writers are just interested in 
watching how people change or dont grow in hardship thats 
usually a premise in every single book said miller author of 
the bestselling the good mother 
so heres a novel about a family unique in the way that all 
unhappy families are unique david and lainey eberhardt live in 
chicago with their two children mack and liddie theyre 
wonderfully undramatically happy 
but their third child randall is autistic its the 1950s a 
time when little was understood about that condition david a 
psychiatrist blames lainey though they have three more children 
nina mary and sarah the marriage falls apart 
i feel the particular time and place the particular set of 
values the psychiatric wisdom of the time has an unbelieveable 
impact on the family its absolutely of this world of its time 
said miller who grew up in chicago in the 50s and 60s and was 
the second of four children 
david has the attitude that orthodox psychiatry had about 
autism and he would have been less likely to sustain those beliefs 
in another time she said referring to his attitude that the 
autism was caused by the mothers behavior 
i think also the very life of that family the father who 
works the mother whose life is her children is very much that 
particular period also the father who is the authoritative figure 
who understands the world who analyzes the world while women were 
supposedly incapacitated by their emotions 
family pictures tells of action and reflection the chapters 
arranged in time like the pages of a family album miller shows her 
characters lying awake in bed rehashing events at bars dousing 
themselves with beer or stealing away from parties to be alone 
with their thoughts 
the novel begins with nina recalling macks 14th birthday 
during which randall amazingly utters happy birthday dear 
mackie at least thats how nina remembers it her mother 
insists it never happened that randall stopped speaking when he 
was 4 and liddie is sure shes the one who should be telling the 
story 
but thats the way it is in a family isnt it miller 
writes the stories get passed around polished embellished 
liddies version or macks version changes as it becomes my 
version 
family pictures is millers version stories are borrowed 
from her own life and others she writes about family outings 
baseball games a chicago college house and the casual cruelty of 
teenage boys 
i do think that its probably easier for women now to imagine 
being male than it was 25 or 35 years ago the way women are now 
raised to think about their sexuality has really shifted 
enormously miller said 
i think that more and more we at least understand and are 
familiar with the other sex women live more like men they have 
much more freedom it possibly has made a women fiction writers 
life easier 
miller a single parent for 12 years now living with her second 
husband rejects the idea that men are more capable of writing 
about the real world the workplace and wars while women are 
better off with the inner world of family novels 
she observes that classic 19thcentury novels such as anna 
karenina and madame bovary were only about families yet 
so rooted in a place and time they defined a whole society as well 
it seems to me the family novel can raise rather large social 
issues as well as rather large philosophical issues in the 19th 
century the people who wrote were often gentlemen so they didnt 
have the rough tough world to write about 
they didnt write about the office they tended to write about 
dinner parties they tended to write about adulteries its a shame 
that its so divided now its seen as this radical feminist 
thing 
in the good mother a woman divorces her lawyer husband and 
begins a passionate affair with an artist when her exhusband 
accuses her lover of sexual irregularities a bitter custody 
battle ensues for their 4yearold daughter the title becomes 
ironic can a woman be a good mother and still enjoy full 
sexual freedom 
family pictures is ironic too the story delivering little 
of the cozy warmth promised by the title like finding graffiti on 
the back of an old framed portrait 
in both novels miller concentrates on the uneasy partnership of 
public and private moving from office rooms to bedrooms tracing 
the confusing intricate paths of the legal and medical professions 
and showing how they can alter the fine print of the human heart 
i feel very connected to particular social issues miller 
said im very interested in the way the law interacts with human 
life the emotional life of human beings and i think its almost 
criminal the particular stance psychiatry took on autism this was 
an error 
for every writer theres the question of what will people 
struggle with what will be the hard thing that happens that people 
will have to grow around or be defeated by in family pictures i 
wanted it to happen over a long period of time i wanted the way 
they thought about it to shift and change 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

