<TEXT>
three equities markets announced this morning 
they have reached a definitive agreement to trade through the night 
using a computer network 
the chicago board options exchange the american stock exchange 
and the cincinnati stock exchange hope to capture some of the 
trading conducted abroad when it is nighttime in the united states 
the computer network would be provided by reuters holdings plc 
the exchanges expect the system will begin working in two to 
three years providing a market from 6 pm to 6 am officials 
said at news conferences in new york and chicago 
the cboe and amex would handle their stock options through the 
system and the cincinnati stock exchange would offer ustraded 
stocks the specific number of issues involved in the system has 
not been decided officials said 
many of the details of how the system will work have yet to be 
determined officials of the exchanges said at the press 
conferences which were linked via television the cboe would build 
and operate the main computer for the system and reuters would 
build the network that provides traders access to the markets 
computer 
other exchanges specifically the new york stock exchange and 
the tokyo exchange have been invited to join the system officials 
said 
although the three exchanges will be cooperating in the 
electronic system james r jones chairman and chief executive of 
the american stock exchange said there still will be competition 
we will continue to have great competition in the daytime 
he said i think this will actually increase competition 
globally 
the groups intention to work toward an automated afterhours 
trading system was first announced in march 1989 officials said 
last weeks announcement of plans for latenight trading by the 
nyse did not prompt todays announcement officials said they 
added however they were aware the nyse was considering 
afterhours trading 
by 1991 the nyse plans to hold three auctions through the night 
of each listed stock each stock would trade once at each auction 
with trades combined at a single price 
the definitive agreement was reached about a month ago and the 
boards of the companies involved finished approving the plan late 
last week 
</TEXT>
