<TEXT>
the supreme court agreed monday to resolve 
conflicting rulings over unions legal duty to cooperate with 
candidates for union office who want to distribute campaign 
literature 
the justices said they will decide whether a maritime industry 
union violated federal labor law when in 1988 it refused to give a 
membership mailing list to a candidate for the unions presidency 
labor law gives candidates for union office a right to have 
campaign literature distributed by the union the court must decide 
whether that right is conditioned by the reasonableness of the 
request for distribution or the reasonableness of a union rule 
restricting such requests 
a decision is expected sometime next year 
the appeal acted on today was filed by the international 
organization of masters mates and pilots a 7500 national union 
representing ship officers pilots and other merchant marine 
workers 
the union based in baltimore holds elections every four years 
prior to the nominating convention for the 1988 election 
presidential candidate timothy a brown a ship captain from tampa 
fla asked the union for mailing labels containing the names and 
addresses of all voting union members 
brown wished to distribute literature at his own expense before 
the nominating convention 
he said he sought to attract support from other members before 
they were likely to have committed their votes to other candidates 
the early mailing also would help offset the advantage held by 
incumbent union officers who might seek reelection 
elwood kyser a union officer turned down browns request 
because the unions constitution does not authorize distribution of 
campaign literature until after a nominating convention 
brown sued and a federal judge in baltimore ordered the union 
to furnish the mailing labels so that browns campaign literature 
could be distributed 
the 4th us circuit court of appeals upheld the order last nov 
17 by an 82 vote 
we believe the test to be not whether the unions rule was 
reasonable but whether the candidates request was reasonable 
the apeals court said 
another federal appeals court ruled otherwise 
asked for their views bush administration lawyers said the 4th 
circuit courts ruling is correct but urged the high court to use 
the case to resolve the conflicting decisions 
the case is international organization of masters mates amp 
pilots vs brown 891330 
