the nations chief federal bank 
regulator watching credit across the northeast dry up amid rising 
loan losses tried to reassure jittery bankers and their customers 
monday that the industry is sound 
comptroller of the currency robert clarke told a group of 
providence executives that the federal government has not toughened 
its regulations or its audits of banks what it has done he said 
is reacted to changes in the economy and in the process has 
uncovered bad loans at many institutions 
were trying to make sure you have a safe and sound banking 
system and at the same time not choke off the availability of 
credit he said 
clarke conceded that a wave of examination of real 
estaterelated bank credit have made it tougher get a loan 
although examiners ordered many of the northeasts largest banks to 
increase their reserves to cover potentially bad loans regulators 
did not advise against continuing to lend money he said 
im concerned about the misconceptions and misperceptions 
about what bank supervisors and the office of the comptroller of 
the currency are doing he said there is no doubt confusion 
in the minds of bankers about what were doing 
the comptroller is focusing much of his attention on new 
england where some business leaders say a regional economic 
