<TEXT>
foreign ministers of the european community 
agreed monday some economic sanctions against south africa could be 
lifted before the government abolishes entirely its racial policy 
of apartheid 
but the ministers of the 12nation trading bloc did not announce 
the immediate easing of any bans imposed against the whiteled 
government 
there was not a majority in favor of the lifting of the 
sanctions said irish foreign minister gerry collins whose 
government has opposed any change in the measures ireland 
currently holds the rotating presidency of the trading bloc 
but he said the ministers did agree that something very 
important is happening in south africa 
in an effort to pressure the government to end its policy of 
racial segregation the community decided in 1986 to halt imports 
of south african iron steel and gold coins and to ban new 
investment in that country it had previously prohibited the sales 
of military equipment 
britain has been pressing the community to ease the sanctions 
because of recent reform measures by south african president fw 
de klerk in february britain unilaterally lifted the ban on new 
investment 
black leader nelson mandela has urged the community to continue 
pressuring de klerks government 
douglas hurd britains foreign secretary said all the 
community nations now have backed a stepbystep strategy under 
which the sanctions could be lifted gradually as progress was made 
on scrapping apartheid 
he said the communitys view was you do not have to wait for 
apartheid to end before you begin to relax the pressures on the 
south african government 
no one argued that the sanctions should remain until the 
complete dismantlement of apartheid agreed a dutch source who 
demanded anonymity 
but hurd said there was no consensus on when the first step 
should be taken 
sources say only ireland and denmark have argued against any 
change in the sanctions 
hurd said some countries want to send a signal of encouragement 
to de klerk perhaps by lifting one of the bans next month 
he said the logical first step would be to relax the 
prohibition on new investment in south africa 
but he said other countries were not so clear about that and 
were not really ready to go that far 
there is a spectrum of opinion on that subject he said 
collins noted that de klerk had lifted the governments state of 
emergency in three of south africas four provinces the decree had 
been in effect for four years 
he said not all the countrys political prisoners have been 
freed from prison although the prospects seem to be good that 
