<DOCNO> AP900618-0236 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court on monday allowed the 
commodity futures trading commission to regulate a type of stock 
market investment called an index participation 
the court without comment left intact an appeals court ruling 
that gives the cftc rather than the securities and exchange 
commission such regulatory power 
an index participation is a contract of indefinite duration 
based on the value of a group of securities the contract resembles 
a basket of stocks because its value is tied to a broad 
stockmarket index such as the standard amp poors 500 index 
the appeals court held that such products come under the cftcs 
supervision if they have any element of a futures contract 
the sec generally regulates securities and the cftc has 
jurisdiction over futures contracts 
the chicagobased 7th us circuit court of appeals said last 
year an index participation has elements of both a security and a 
futures contract but the appeals court said the cftc has exclusive 
jurisdiction over the investment instrument 
the appeals court ruling was challenged by the american stock 
exchange the chicago board options exchange the philadelphia 
stock exchange and the options clearing corp the american and the 
latter organization issues options that are traded on the exchanges 
the president of the philadelphia exchange nicholas a 
giordano called the supreme court action a major step backward 
in the regulation and development of innovative new products 
the real loser here is the individual investor for whom index 
participations were originally designed he said in a statement 
lost in the debate over legislative authority on these products 
was the elemental fact that far fewer brokers are qualified to 
trade futures than are to trade securities 
bob shabazian a spokesman for the american stock exchange said 
the amex had no comment on the courts action but added that the 
exchange supported a bill before congress that would shift 
regulation of all stock index futures from the cftc to the sec 
the bush administration which had urged the supreme court not 
to disturb the 7th circuit court ruling also supports the bill 
but the proposal has received a cool reception on capitol hill 
where some critics say the proposal could hinder passage of other 
measures designed to give the sec more power to curb wall street 
volatility 
the plan to reduce the cftcs power was prompted by rulings by 
the 7th circuit and other courts that give the cftc exclusive 
regulatory authority over any financial product with even the 
slightest aspect of a futures contract 
sec and treasury department officials have complained those 
rulings have led to long legal battles over jurisdiction while 
innovative financial products are being developed or copied in 
overseas markets 
index participations for example are available only on the 
toronto stock exchange and not on any us exchange 
the cases are investment company institute vs sec 891484 
american stock exchange vs chicago mercantile exchange 891502 
philadelphia stock exchange vs chicago mercantile exchange 
891503 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

