<TEXT>
the commerce department said monday it is 
dropping the requirements for export licenses on about 30 billion 
worth of trade in computers telecommunications equipment and other 
high technology goods 
undersecretary dennis kloske said the liberalized requirements 
which will take effect in early july will eliminate the need for 
about 20000 export licenses a year 
the new requirements cover products shipped to us allies in 
the coordinating committee for multilateral export controls the 
17nation group known as cocom polices hightechnology exports in 
an effort to keep militarily sensitive products from being diverted 
to communist countries 
with the toppling of communist governments throughout eastern 
europe the united states has been under heavy pressure from its 
allies to relax export restrictions 
this new regulation is one of the most significant steps to 
relax strategic trade controls with our cocom allies in the 
postwar era kloske said it means giving us businesses an 
even better chance to compete in the international marketplace 
the department said it will continue to require licenses for 
shipments of some sensitive hightechnology items such as 
supercomputers the 20000 export licenses being eliminated are 
among 85000 total export licenses issued each year by the us 
government 
still the relaxed requirement the outcome of three years of 
negotiations will bring the us and its allies closer to a 
licensefree zone within their borders 
the announcement monday will provide for additional streamlining 
of controls beyond changes that were approved at a cocom meeting 
earlier this month in paris the paris meeting dealt with 
restrictions on the types of products which could be sold to former 
communist bloc countries in eastern europe 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

