<TEXT>
motorola inc said a federal judge 
indicated monday he would require the company to pull a key 
computer chip off the market until a lawsuit over the chips patent 
is resolved 
but motorola engaged in a legal fight over trade secrets with 
former partner hitachi ltd said it would appeal the decision 
immediately after it is reported by us district judge lucius 
bunton of midland 
in a statement from its schaumburg ill headquarters motorola 
said such a decision might temporarily halt the sale of its 
marketleading 68030 microprocessor which is made in austin 
but motorola said it expected the decision would be stayed on 
appeal and that it is confident it would continue to provide an 
uninterrupted supply of the microprocessor to customers 
buntons order was to be released through the federal district 
clerks office in austin according to his office but the ruling 
was unavailable by the time the office closed monday at 5 pm 
said deputy us district clerk bob williams 
motorola said bunton had disclosed his intent to sign the order 
but had not yet signed it 
tokyobased hitachi filed the motion with bunton to temporarily 
halt the sale of the motorola microprocessor an attorney for 
hitachi in chicago jerry solovy had no immediate comment 
bunton banned the sale of the chip on march 29 and fined both 
companies saying they violated each others patents 
but the prohibition was reversed a day later after motorola 
argued that the chip sales ban could devastate outside computer 
makers that depend on its microprocessors to run their machines 
on monday motorola said bunton indicated he would lift his stay 
on the injunction thereby preventing motorola from selling its 
microprocessor and hitachi from selling its own dubbed the h8532 
tim kellogg spokesman for motorola said the company would file 
its appeal with the us court of appeals for the federal circuit 
following buntons decision the court is a special appeals court 
for patents and customs in washington 
we are confident that the cafc will promptly stay the lower 
courts decision pending appeal motorola said in a statement 
it added we are dismayed that judge bunton made this decision 
knowing full well that the two parties have been engaged in earnest 
attempts to settle this matter 
</TEXT>
